Fixes Landed — April 16 Session
Each entry tagged "sim-verified" (checked in simulator only) or "iPad retest needed" (touch/Pencil-dependent, must confirm on Paige iPad).

[~] Text tool crash + white rectangle — sim-verifiable; iPad retest needed for placement accuracy at non-default zoom
    Root cause: two bugs in one path.
      (1) CanvasStateManager.renderText passed `screenSize` (UIKit pts ~1194) to
          CanvasRenderer.renderText while `location` was already in document
          space (~2048). The renderer multiplied location by texture/screenSize
          ≈1.72×, walking destinationOrigin off the texture; blitEncoder.copy
          Metal-asserted → crash.
      (2) blitEncoder.copy is a raw byte copy with no alpha blending. The
          rasterized text image's transparent margins overwrote anything beneath
          the text rect, leaving a transparent hole that revealed the white
          canvas background — the visible "white rectangle".
    Fix:
      • CanvasStateManager.renderText now passes `documentSize` (1:1 with
        texture in current architecture).
      • CanvasRenderer.renderText rewritten to rasterize text to a
        scale=1.0 UIImage, then route through the existing renderImage path
        which uses the proven premultiplied Porter-Duff blend (same path
        moved selections use). No new blending math, no destructive blit.
      • Added before/after snapshots so text placement is now undoable.
      • Thumbnail refresh after text commits.
    Files: CanvasStateManager.swift, CanvasRenderer.swift

[~] Image import broken — sim-verifiable
    Root cause: importImage() called addLayer() then immediately tried to render
    into layers[selectedLayerIndex].texture — but addLayer only appends the
    DrawingLayer to the array. Texture creation is lazy inside
    MetalCanvasView.Coordinator.ensureLayerTextures(), which only runs during a
    Metal draw cycle. So at the moment of the import call the texture was nil,
    the guard returned early, and the image never landed on the layer. The
    PhotosPicker showed and dismissed normally, masking the silent failure.
    Fix:
      • importImage now eagerly calls renderer.createLayerTexture() right after
        addLayer, before the render call. Coordinator.ensureLayerTextures will
        skip the layer next draw because it already has a texture.
      • Undo still works via the existing .layerAdded history record (undo
        removes the layer + image together; redo re-inserts the same DrawingLayer
        whose texture is retained).
    Files: CanvasStateManager.swift

[x] Cut Rotate Left / Rotate Right toolbar buttons — sim-verified (visual only)
    Reason: redundant with two-finger pinch-rotate which works on device.
    Fix: removed both ToolButton entries from DrawingCanvasView's toolbar grid.
    The viewfinder/recenter button stays — it resets all transforms.
    Files: DrawingCanvasView.swift

[x] Canvas zoom % moved out from behind gallery icon — sim-verified
    Root cause: zoom indicator was a top-trailing VStack overlay that stacked
    in the same screen region as the gallery button (50×50 pinned top-trailing
    with .padding 12pt). At any zoom ≠ 100% the readout rendered behind the
    larger gallery icon and was invisible.
    Fix:
      • Removed the zoom block from the top-right indicator VStack (rotation
        indicator stays — it doesn't conflict with the gallery icon).
      • Added a persistent zoom % readout at the top of the floating toolbar,
        always visible. Tapping it resets zoom/pan/rotation (same action as
        the existing recenter button).
    Files: DrawingCanvasView.swift

[~] Onboarding keyboard squashing form layout — sim-verifiable
    Root cause: PromptInputView centered the card with two Spacers and a
    .frame(maxHeight: 700). When the iOS software keyboard appeared, the safe
    area shrank, the available height for the centering VStack shrank, and the
    card compressed proportionally — squashing the form fields off-screen with
    no auto-scroll to the focused field.
    Fix:
      • Added .ignoresSafeArea(.keyboard, edges: .bottom) on the outer ZStack
        so the layout no longer compresses when the keyboard appears.
      • Added @FocusState tracking which TextField has focus (subject, style,
        artists, techniques, focus).
      • Wrapped the form ScrollView in a ScrollViewReader and tagged each
        field VStack with .id(Field.x). On focus change, scrolls the focused
        field to anchor: .top with a 0.05s delay so layout settles first.
        Anchor .top (vs .center) because with the keyboard safe area ignored
        the ScrollView gets no automatic bottom inset — pinning to .top
        guarantees the field sits well above the keyboard regardless of card
        height.
      • Sticky bottom buttons remain sticky and may be visually overlapped by
        the keyboard; user can swipe-dismiss (scrollDismissesKeyboard already
        wired up) to access them.
    Files: PromptInputView.swift

[~] AI feedback panel sizing + default to most recent — sim-verifiable
    Root cause: three problems in one panel.
      (1) Fixed expandedSize (656×625) didn't respect screen geometry. On
          smaller screens or split-screen the panel could exceed bounds.
      (2) The history menu slid out 200pt to the LEFT of the panel. When the
          panel sat at its default top-left position (~20pt from screen left),
          opening the history slid the menu to x = -188 — fully off-screen.
      (3) selectedHistoryIndex defaulted to 0, which pointed at the OLDEST
          critique (the menu reverses the array for display, so the newest is
          on top, but the index stayed pinned to the array's first element).
          Opening the panel showed stale feedback every time.
    Fix:
      • Added computed `actualExpandedSize` clamped to
        max(320, screenSize - padding - menuRoom). The fixed expandedSize
        (656×625) becomes the upper bound, not the literal size. All .frame,
        boundary, and offset calculations switched to actualExpandedSize.
      • When the user taps the history menu button, if the panel is too close
        to the screen's left edge, we slide the panel right just enough that
        the 200pt menu has room to appear without clipping.
      • selectedHistoryIndex is set to max(0, critiqueHistory.count - 1) on
        the panel's .onAppear AND on .onChange(of: critiqueHistory.count), so
        the panel always opens on (and stays on) the latest critique.
    Files: FloatingFeedbackPanel.swift


